Londen Samuel Blewitt
sence my last of u curs non from you I have not been hable to
compleat your order to come with the vessel of martin Iohn son, parteley
because I had severall formar ordr, butt the most reason is, that thes
garmans thiad markett is now, till michaelmas, & they lake in
payement, oft their thrad all the tykes that they can come ssak now so that
I must stay a little: yett I have shipped, by the vessel of martin Johnson
75 pigsces, accordingly to the inclosed invoyce, & bill of loadinge for which
please to give mee creditiis not your mark or number, butt this
pack was designed for an other, so to serve you in part of your commision
have forwarded for youy the vessel, wendt from hence 2 dayes agoe
& intendes to saile from ostend by the first convoy, which they writte
from thence to bee, bound, god send them well to you: whilst
I shall provide the remainder of your order butt pray advise me if I
may adsone more, to make them up n areasonable pack in exspectation
of your advise I rest
25 gber
Londen Richard Southeel
mij last to you was 18 curd, then ordered you to provide 10 single
beds viz one doublep of £10 a 2 of £11 & one of £11:10 aƒ 12
with one arorar, of £12 a £13 which now I confirme, butt I
vere
am informed, as if the agrovar deaver, then formerley, so
that I doubt you shall not finde the qualitie, of goodnes & passe
fe & cullour I exspect, therefore desire you, to buy no aprovaz
except itt bee of a deep cullour & as neare the scarlett as possible
& if not well to content rather to buy one more double red of £10:-
echipide
& lave the arrovan behinde. I am vere much disapointted to have
the tykes I designed for you, by this vessel of martin John son
the man, I bought thene of, beinge sence my last, & the
de ay
bussiness in kome confusion, there was 150 pieces & I had al readdy
given some monney upon accompt, butt I hope not to loose, never theles
I have ferwarded to you what I hade readdye, according to the
inolosed envoyce & bill of loadinge a month to £63„ 5„10 en which
drawne a 33 „ 9 et makes £37:10 a1 en for which please to give my
accompt credit I shall endeavour to gett the 150 pieces bespoohey &
sende them part or all to you the red cloathes I order must come by
the first convoij for ostend, or clee not for then time, shall bee
past, in exspectacien. what passes I remaine.
25 gber

my last to you was 22 seurs, sence recd yours of 6 ditto, with bills of
loadinge of N. 79: & 80 att hull for amstt, which is well & doubt not
butt you shall gett the bayes also in time for this convoye, & see you have
shipped 4 packs abrard John hazelwood att which I were much wonder,
for I have alwayes ordered you, & recommended to devide my risico &
never to ship above £200 valeuw in one bottem, besaides, I have writt
you in march last that I was in formed that John hazelwood is a meere
laggered & fitter for a cabinge boye then a ship masser, & y ett you
